                <p>Interface Illustration</p>
                <img src="/image/rapport1.png" alt="Description de l'image" width="900" height="600" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:8px;" />
            </div>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>Important Notes</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>The report does not include invoice discounts.</li>
                <li>Returns and discounts are included in global calculations.</li>
                <li>All amounts are in FCFA unless currency is changed.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>
    </section>


    <!-- Section 2: Purchase and Sale -->
    <section class="section-2">
        <h2>2) Purchase and Sale</h2>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>2.1) Purpose of this Interface</h3>
            <p>
                The Purchase and Sale report effectively compares company purchases against recorded sales to evaluate:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>The gross profitability of operations,</li>
                <li>Discrepancies between amounts spent and recovered,</li>
                <li>Outstanding payments to suppliers (purchase due) or from customers (sale due),</li>
                <li>And detect operational imbalances.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                This is a synthetic view ideal for managers, financial officers, or business owners.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>2.2) Interface Structure</h3>
            <p>
                The interface is divided into 3 main sections:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Filters (location and dates)</li>
                <li>Summary blocks: Purchases vs Sales</li>
                <li>Final analytical summary</li>
            </ul>

            <h4>2.2.1) Analysis Filters</h4>
            <p>
                <strong>Location (site):</strong><br>
                Selects the activity site (store, depot, warehouse) to analyze<br>
                <strong>Date filter:</strong><br>
                Allows selecting a <strong>specific time range to generate the report (e.g., monthly, quarterly)</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                These filters ensure <strong>temporal and geographical targeting of the report.</strong>
            </p>

            <h4>2.2.2) Summary Blocks (Purchases vs Sales)</h4>
            <h5>Purchases Block (left)</h5>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Line</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total purchase</td>
                    <td>Total purchase amount (excluding tax) during the selected period</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Purchase incl. tax</td>
                    <td>Purchase amount including tax (if applicable)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total purchase return incl. tax</td>
                    <td>Return on investment or profit on tax-inclusive purchases (in this view: 0.00 FCFA, so no profit calculated)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Purchase due</td>
                    <td>Total amounts not yet paid to suppliers</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <p>
                This block tracks financial commitments related to procurement.
            </p>

            <h5>Sales Block (right)</h5>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Line</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total sale</td>
                    <td>Total sales amount (excluding tax)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Sale incl. tax</td>
                    <td>Sales amount including tax</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total sale return incl. tax</td>
                    <td>Represents total net gain (in this case 0.00 FCFA, as no accounting variation recorded)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Sale due</td>
                    <td>Total sales not yet collected (debtor customers)</td>
                </tr>
            </table>

            <h4>2.2.3) Consolidated Financial Summary</h4>
            <p>
                Located at the bottom, this panel provides a direct readout of results.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Sale – Purchase:</strong><br>
                Calculation of <strong>gross margin = Total sales – Total purchases = 817,000 FCFA (theoretical profit)</strong><br>
                <strong>Amount due:</strong><br>
                Net remaining debt, calculated as:<br>
                (Purchase due – Sale due) = -18,000 FCFA, meaning a payment is still <strong>due to the supplier.</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                ☺ <strong>Green value (profit):</strong> indicates that sales generated a surplus compared to purchases.<br>
                ☻ <strong>Red value (amount due):</strong> alerts about unpaid supplier commitments.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>2.3) Additional Features</h3>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Button</th>
                    <th>Function</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Print</td>
                    <td>Generates a paper or PDF version of the report for archiving or presentation</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Blue tooltips</td>
                    <td>Help understand the exact meaning of each line (e.g., calculation of totals or returns)</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <div class="image-placeholder">
                <p>Interface Illustration</p>
                <img src="/image/rapport2.png" alt="Description de l'image" width="900" height="600" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:8px;" />
            </div>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>Usage Recommendations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Ensure all sales and purchases are recorded for the period.</li>
                <li>Verify that <strong>related payments</strong> are up to date to avoid a <strong>false balance.</strong></li>
                <li>Consult this report <strong>weekly/monthly to anticipate cash flow management.</strong></li>
                <li>Use this report before <strong>restocking to compare profitability.</strong></li>
            </ul>
        </article>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: Tax Report -->
    <section class="section-3">
        <h2>3) Tax Report</h2>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>3.1) Purpose of this Interface</h3>
            <p>
                The "Tax Report" interface allows the company to:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Track tax application on various transactions (purchases, sales, expenses),</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Establish precise tax statements for monthly/quarterly declarations,</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Prepare tax reports for authorities (VAT, service tax, etc.),</strong></li>
                <li>And justify tax credits/debits during audits or regular accounting.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                This is a key interface for accountants, financial officers, or administrative managers.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>3.2) Interface Composition</h3>
            <p>
                The interface is divided into three main sections:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Viewing filters</li>
                <li>Global tax balance summary</li>
                <li>Detailed tables by tax type (with tabs)</li>
            </ul>

            <h4>3.2.1) Viewing Filters</h4>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Element</th>
                    <th>Function</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Company location</td>
                    <td>Selects a specific site or all sites combined</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Contact</td>
                    <td>Filters reports by relevant supplier or customer</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Date range</td>
                    <td>Defines the tax analysis period (e.g., 01/01/2025 – 31/12/2025 in the screenshot)</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <p>
                These filters ensure <strong>targeted analysis compliant with the relevant tax period.</strong>
            </p>

            <h4>3.2.2) Global Tax Summary (central banner)</h4>
            <p>
                The central line of the interface indicates:
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>"Downstream tax - Upstream tax - Expense tax: FCFA 0.00"</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                This corresponds to a global tax balance:
            </p>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Term</th>
                    <th>Definition</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Downstream tax</td>
                    <td>Total tax collected on sales (VAT charged to customers)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Upstream tax</td>
                    <td>Tax borne by the company on purchases (VAT paid to suppliers)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Expense tax</td>
                    <td>Taxes applied to other charges (e.g., fuel, external fees)</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <p>
                <strong>Basic formula used to declare VAT due:</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Net VAT = Downstream tax – Upstream tax – Expense tax</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                In the example: no movement recorded yet, hence a zero balance (FCFA 0.00).
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>3.2.3) Tax Analysis Tables (with tabs)</h3>
            <p>
                This section appears as three distinct tabs, each containing a <strong>detailed table:</strong>
            </p>

            <h4>a) Input Tax Tab (Purchases)</h4>
            <p>
                This table displays all taxes collected during purchases.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Main columns:</strong></p>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Column</th>
                    <th>Role</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Date</td>
                    <td>Purchase transaction date</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Reference number</td>
                    <td>Purchase order or invoice reference</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Supplier</td>
                    <td>Name of the concerned supplier</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Tax identification number</td>
                    <td>Supplier's IFU/NIF number</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total amount</td>
                    <td>Total invoice amount including tax</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Payment method</td>
                    <td>Cash, transfer, credit, etc.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Discount</td>
                    <td>Discounts applied to the purchase</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <p>
                This report is essential to justify VAT deductibility on purchases.
            </p>

            <h4>b) Downstream Tax Tab (Sales)</h4>
            <p>
                This table groups taxes collected on sales.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Main columns:</strong></p>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Column</th>
                    <th>Role</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Date</td>
                    <td>Purchase transaction date</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Invoice number</td>
                    <td>Unique identifier for each invoice</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Customer</td>
                    <td>Name of the concerned customer</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Tax identification number</td>
                    <td>Customer's IFU/NIF number</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total amount</td>
                    <td>Total invoice amount including tax</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Payment method</td>
                    <td>Cash, transfer, credit, etc.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Discount</td>
                    <td>Discounts applied to the purchase</td>
                </tr>
            </table>

            <h4>c) Expense Tax Tab</h4>
            <p>
                Designed for <strong>non-trading charges (e.g., phone, transport, energy), this tab</strong>
                justifies taxes unrelated to stock or merchandise purchases.
            </p>
            <p>Main columns:</p>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Column</th>
                    <th>Role</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Date</td>
                    <td>Purchase transaction date</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Reference number</td>
                    <td>Purchase order or invoice reference</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Tax identification number</td>
                    <td>Supplier's IFU/NIF number</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total amount</td>
                    <td>Total invoice amount including tax</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Payment method</td>
                    <td>Cash, transfer, credit, etc.</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>3.3) Additional Functions</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>✓ <strong>CSV / Excel / PDF Export:</strong> Generates user reports in the desired format.</li>
                <li>✓ <strong>Direct printing:</strong> A print button is available to produce a paper version of the list.</li>
                <li>✓ <strong>Column visibility:</strong> Allows hiding or displaying certain columns based on preferences.</li>
                <li>✓ <strong>Dynamic search:</strong> A quick search field helps locate specific users.</li>
                <li>✓ <strong>Pagination & entries per page:</strong> Users can navigate between pages and choose how many records to display per page (e.g., 10, 25, 50).</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="image-placeholder">
                <p>Interface Illustration</p>
                <img src="/image/rapport3.png" alt="Description de l'image" width="900" height="600" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:8px;" />
            </div>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>Practical Recommendations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>This report should be generated at the end of each month or before any tax declaration.</li>
                <li>It is essential to correctly enter VAT rates during purchases/sales in the system to ensure tax data consistency.</li>
                <li>Use the "Tax identification number" field for strict tax compliance.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: Supplier and Customer Report -->
    <section class="section-4">
        <h2>4) Supplier and Customer Report</h2>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>4.1) Purpose of this Interface</h3>
            <p>
                The Supplier and Customer Report interface in Movelys provides a consolidated view of commercial transactions (purchases and sales) conducted with each contact registered in the system (customer or supplier).
            </p>
            <p>
                It offers direct insight into <strong>amounts committed, payments received or made, and</strong>
                remaining outstanding balances.
            </p>
            <p>
                This functionality is essential for:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Tracking <strong>supplier and customer accounts,</strong></li>
                <li>Identifying <strong>unpaid amounts or credits to recover,</strong></li>
                <li>Managing financial relationships by third party.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>4.2) General Interface Structure</h3>
            <p>
                The interface consists of three main areas:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Filter and search bar</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Transaction summary table</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Export and print functions</strong></li>
            </ul>

            <h4>4.2.1) Filter and Search Bar</h4>
            <p>
                It contains the following elements:
            </p>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Column</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Customer group name</td>
                    <td>Name of the concerned customer group.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Type</td>
                    <td>Nature of the relationship between the contact and the company (customer, supplier)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Location</td>
                    <td>Operation point (store, depot, service)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Contact</td>
                    <td>Name of the concerned customer or supplier.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Date range</td>
                    <td>Analyzed time interval</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <p>
                These filters enable <strong>targeted consultation, facilitating audits or tracking of specific</strong>
                third parties.
            </p>

            <h4>4.2.2) Transaction Summary Table</h4>
            <p>
                This dynamic table centralizes all financial data by contact.
                Each line corresponds to a <strong>third party (customer or supplier) and displays the following indicators:</strong>
            </p>
            <table class="component-table">
                <tr>
                    <th>Contact</th>
                    <th>Name of the concerned customer or supplier.</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total purchase</td>
                    <td>Total sum of purchases made from the contact (if supplier)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Contact number</td>
                    <td>Contact's phone number.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total purchase return</td>
                    <td>Total sum of purchases made from the contact (if supplier).</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total sale</td>
                    <td>Total amount of goods returned to the supplier (purchase returns)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total sale return</td>
                    <td>Total amount of products returned by the customer to the company, due to non-compliance or cancellation.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Opening balance due</td>
                    <td>Balance prior to the first use of the software or contact registration.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Due</td>
                    <td>Remaining balance that the customer or company still needs to pay at the report consultation date.</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <p>
                This table provides a bilateral view (purchases and sales), very useful for hybrid partners
                (both customers and suppliers).
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="subsection">
            <h3>4.2.3) Additional Features</h3>
            <p>
                Located at the top or right of the interface:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>✓ <strong>CSV / Excel / PDF Export:</strong> Generates user reports in the desired format.</li>
                <li>✓ <strong>Direct printing:</strong> A print button is available to produce a paper version of the list.</li>
